  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-equations-of-planes">
    <title>Equations of Planes and Hyperplanes</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the equation of the plane with normal
          <m>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -1 \\ -1 \\ 0
            \end{matrix} \right)
          </m> if 
          <m>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              0 \\ 1 \\ 3 
            \end{matrix} \right)
          </m> is a point on the plane. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The normal determines the coefficients of the equation of
          the plane. We put those coefficients into the general form,
          with the constant <m>d</m> undetermined.
          <m>
            (-1)x + (-1)y + 0 z = d 
          </m>
          We can calculate the constant using the point. Put the
          corodinates of the point into the left side of the equation
          and calculate <m>d</m> 
          <m>
            d = (-1)(0) + (-1)(1) + (0)(3) = -1 
          </m>
          Therefore, the equation of the plane is 
          <m>
            - x - y = -1 
          </m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the equation of the plane with normal
          <m>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              2 \\ 0 \\ 3
            \end{matrix} \right)
          </m> if 
          <m>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -4 \\ -1 \\ 2
            \end{matrix} \right)
          </m> is a point on the plane. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The normal determines the coefficients of the equation of
          the plane. We put those coefficients into the general form,
          with the constant <m>d</m> undetermined.
          <m>
            2x + 0y + 3z = d 
          </m>
          We can calculate the constant using the point. Put the
          corodinates of the point into the left side of the equation
          and calculate <m>d</m> 
          <m>
            d = 2(-4) + 0(-1) + 3(2) = -2 
          </m>
          Therefore, the equation of the plane is 
          <m>
            2x + 3z = -2 
          </m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the equation of the plane with local direcitons
          <m>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -1 \\ -1 \\ 1 
            \end{matrix} \right)
          </m> and
          <m>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -2 \\ 1 \\ 0 
            \end{matrix} \right)
          </m> if 
          <m>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              2 \\ 1 \\ 1
            \end{matrix} \right)
          </m> is a point on the plane. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The cross product of the local direcitons gives the normal
          to the plane. 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -1 \\ -1 \\ 1 
            \end{matrix} \right) \times 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -2 \\ 1 \\ 0 
            \end{matrix} \right) = 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              (-1)(0) - (1)(1) \\ (1)(-2) - (-1)(0) \\ (-1)(1) -
              (-1)(-2) 
            \end{matrix} \right) = 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -1 \\ -2 \\ -1 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          This is the normal. the normal determines the coefficients
          of the equation of the plane. We put those coefficients into
          the general form, with the constant <m>d</m> undetermined.
          <m>
            -x - 2y - z = d 
          </m>
          We can calculate the constant using the point. Put the
          corodinates of the point into the left side of the equation
          and calculate <m>d</m> 
          <m>
            d = -(2)(2) - (2)(1) - (1) = -7
          </m>
          Therefore, the equation of the plane is 
          <m>
            -x - 2y - z = -7 
          </m>.
        </p>
