  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-sets-structure">
    <title>Sets with Structure</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In <xref ref="section-sets-with-structure" />, I
          introduced the abstract idea of sets with structure. In the
          next two activities, I'm asking you to think through that
          abstract idea. In the first activity, I've given you an
          empty table with some number sets and some possible
          structure. 
          Complete this table by writing <q>Yes</q> or <q>No</q> in
          each space. Write <q>Yes</q> is the set in question include
          the structure (the structure must remain in the set); write
          <q>No</q> if the set does not include the structure. 
        </p>
        <p>
          The set
          <m>\ZZ/12\ZZ</m> is the integers modulo 12. If this set is
          unfamiliar, you may treat it as the numbers on the clock.
          So, for example, if we want to add <m>7 + 9</m>, we ask what
          time is 9 hours after 7, which is 4. Therefore <m>7 + 9 =
          4</m> in an example of proper arithimetic for this set. In
          general, whenever we would get a number larger than
          <m>11</m>, we subtract multiples of <m>12</m> to reduce it
          down to something between <m>0</m> and <m>11</m>. 
          For another example, <m>5 \times 4 = 8</m> is also proper
          arithmetic for this set, since <m>20 - 12 = 8</m>. Note that
          <m>12</m> is the same thing as <m>0</m> in this set; even
          though on a clock we would ofter write <m>12</m>, in this
          set we usually just write <m>0</m>. So, for example, we
          would write <m>5 + 7 = 0</m> in this set. Finally, this is
          just integers modulo 12, so we only consider the whole
          numbers of the clock <mdash /> we don't have minutes or any
          other subdivisions, only hours. 
        </p>
        <p>
          The last term in the table, zero divisors, may not be
          familiar to you. A set has zero divisors if there are two
          non-zero elements <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> which multiply to
          zero.
        </p>
