  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-week2-proofs">
    <title>Proof Questions</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          This is a guided proof to prove the triangle inequality
          using the dot product. The triangle inequality states that,
          for any vector <m>u,v \in \RR^n</m>, the length of the sum
          is bounded by the sum of the lengths of the individual
          vectors. In symbols:
          <me>
            |u+v| \leq |u| + |v|
          </me>.
          I'm going to give you several small steps which fit together
          into a complete proof.
          <ol>
            <li>
              Write <m>|u+v|^2</m> as a dot product.
            </li>
            <li>
              Expand that dot product (distribute the pieces).
            </li>
            <li>
              Replace <m>u \cdot </m> with <m>|u||v| \cos \theta</m>. 
            </li>
            <li>
              Use the fact that <m>\cos \theta \leq 1</m> to make the
              equality into an inequality.
            </li>
            <li>
              Manipulate the inequality to show that <m>|u+v|^2 \leq
              (|u| + |v|)^2</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Take the square root of both sides (which preserves the
              inequality and is well defined since both sides are
              positive). 
            </li>
            <li>
              Conclude the triangle inequality. 
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I'll follow the guided steps for this proof. First, let's
          write <m>|u+v|^2</m> as a dot product. We use the fact that
          the square of the length of a vector is the same as the dot
          product of a vector with itself. 
          <me>
            |u+v|^2 = (u+v) \cdot (u+v)
          </me>
          The next step is to distribute the right side. The dot
          product distributes over vector addition like ordinary
          multipliction. 
          <me>
            |u+v|^2 = u \cdot u + 2 u \cdot v + v \cdot v 
          </me>
          The middle term has the dot product which we can replace as
          instructed.
          <me>
            |u+v|^2 = u \cdot u + 2 |u||v| \cos \theta + v \cdot v 
          </me>
          The greatest that the cosine term can be is 1, so the
          maximum for the right side happens when we repalce the
          cosine with 1. 
          <me>
            |u+v|^2 \leq u \cdot u + 2 |u||v| + v \cdot v 
          </me>
          Then we need to turn the right side into a square term. The
          first step in that direction is to write the dot products
          as squares of lengths. 
          <me>
            |u+v|^2 \leq |u|^2 + 2 |u||v| + |v|^2
          </me>
          Then the right side is the square of a binomial.
          <me>
            |u+v|^2 \leq \left( |u| + |v| \right)^2 
          </me>
          Finally, we take the square root of both sides. 
          <me>
            |u+v| \leq |u| + |v| 
          </me>
          We have produced the triangle inequality.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that the cross product is anticommutative. (Take any
          two vector <m>u,v \in \RR^3</m>, write them in their
          components and prove that <m>u \times v = - (v \times
          u)</m>.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I will start with the right side and try to manipulate it
          into the left side. I'll write the vector in their
          components, use the definition of the cross product, and
          bring in the <m>(-1)</m> using the definition of scalar
          multiplication. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              - (v \times u) \amp = - \left( \left( \begin{matrix}
                v_1 \\ v_2 \\ v_3
              \end{matrix} \right) \times \left( \begin{matrix}
                u_1 \\ u_2 \\ u_3 
              \end{matrix} \right) \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = - \left( \left( \begin{matrix}
                v_2 u_3 - v_3 u_2 \\
                v_3 u_1 - v_1 u_3 \\
                v_1 u_2 - v_2 u_1 
              \end{matrix} \right) \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \left( \begin{matrix}
                - v_2 u_3 + v_3 u_2 \\
                - v_3 u_1 + v_1 u_3 \\
                - v_1 u_2 + v_2 u_1 
              \end{matrix} \right) \right)
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Now I just write each component in the other order,
          interchage the order of the each multiplication, and
          recognize the definition of the cross product. 
          <me>
            = \left( \left( \begin{matrix}
              v_3 u_2 - v_2 u_3 \\
              v_1 u_3 - v_3 u_1 \\
              v_2 u_1 - v_1 u_2 
            \end{matrix} \right) \right)
            = \left( \left( \begin{matrix}
              u_2 v_3 - u_3 v_2 \\
              u_3 v_1 - u_1 v_3 \\
              u_1 v_3 - u_2 v_1 
            \end{matrix} \right) \right) = u \times v
          </me>
          I start with the right side and made a chain of equality to
          the left side, thus proving the identity. 
        </p>
      </solution>
